<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-342-762  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 342 762.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Business  June 12 1989 v15 n12 p80(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>MITI explains why Japan is no copycat these days. (Ministry ofInternational Trade and Industry reports that Japan originates 75percent of its high technology)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Doe, Paula.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Japan uses foreign technology in only 25 percent of its hightechnology production, according to an MITI report.andP;  The Japanesegovernment sought to reduce the dependency of the high techindustry on foreign technology by funding research projectsitself, and the project appears to have worked.andO;Government-sponsored research is responsible for about 10 percentof all technological advancements used.andP;  In the aerospace andtelecommunication equipment industry, home-grown technologyreaches upwards of 90 percent.andP;  Japan's phenomenal success rate intechnology development is due primarily to the quality of Japan'slabor force, MITI reports.andP;  In other areas, especiallysemiconductor memories and microprocessors where dependencyreaches 35 to 40 percent, Japanese corporations are stilldependent on foreign technology from the US and Europe.andP;  MITIpublished its findings in the report, Sangyo Gijutsu no Doko toKadai.'andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Japan. Ministry of International Trade and IndustryTechnology transferResearch and DevelopmentHigh TechnologyJapanGovernment Funding.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Japan's sources of technology for key high technology products.andO;(graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>